Postpartum Depression and Psychosis are serious medical conditions that need to be cared for. I waited too long to receive care becuase I thought what I was going through was normal and that all new parents experienced intrusive thoughts and similar feelings. But it wasn't normal and I was experiencing severe Postpartum Depression and Psychosis. I didn't start getting better until after a three day inpatient hospital stay, starting medication, therapy, and lots of support with Wilder. I got better and am getting better, but only after asking for help. ❤️

#transdad #postpartum #postpartumdepression #postpartumpsychosis #trans #birthingparent #fourthtrimester

I need to take a moment to be super transparent and ask for help, again. 

I'm not doing well. 

These past two months Wilder has entered at sleep regression that has triggered my postpartum depression in big ways. 

Wilder screams (which then triggers Miko to scream) anytime I'm not touching them while they sleep. I'm.not.exaggerating. 

I know I did this to myself and I'm the problem. But the truth is, I can't handle it when my baby cries. It makes my skin crawl and my heart race. To keep them from crying, I would lay with them until they went to sleep, which often takes hours. But then I started not being able to sneak away and now we are here. I have to go to sleep when wilder goes to sleep and wake up when they wake up. If I try to sneak away in the night to use the bathroom Wilder freaks out. 

This has impacted my mental and emotional health in big ways. 

It has also impacted my ability to work and bring in enough to cover December rent and our ability to travel home for the holidays. As a single stay at home parent, I work when Wilder goes to sleep and I get my self care time in before they wake up. I haven't been able to work in almost a month and self-care is MIA. 

I feel completely defeated and deflated. 

My hope was to drive home for Christmas next month so Wilder and I could spend it with my family, rather then being alone. But as of now, I don't even have rent covered let alone a trip home. 

Wilder's birthday is in two days and I don't have one thing planned, one present for them, or a cent to my name. 

It feels like I am failing. And I can't do this alone. 

If you're open and able to help us out this month, it would be deeply appreciated. I'm not a scammer (even though the Reddit worriors are going to eat this up). I'm just a single dad trying my best to make it on my own, but I'm near my breaking point again and need help. 

And please, if you don't have anything nice to say, then don't say anything at all. I'm doing the best I can right now. 

Thank you to everyone for your continued support and you kind words. 

Venmo/cashapp: @dannythetransdad
PayPal: aworld4peace@gmail.com

For the last year now, most days have felt like groundhogs day on repeat while I'm stuck in a state of anxiety trying to figure out how to make it as a single parent. 

This last year I've really struggled trying to figure out how to connect with enough brands as a content creator. I've struggled trying to write my book and get my YouTube channel up and running all while raising Wilder alone. 

But I'm so excited to share that I no longer have to figure it all out on my own and have officially signed with a talent agency! 

I'm so excited to be working with @thegoldstudios and creating magic this next year! I've known for a while now that something needs to change and that I can't do this on my own, so I'm feeling really grateful for this opportunity. 

Not only will they help me get brand deals and financial stability, but they will also be helping me create some of my bigger dreams such as writing a book, going on a speaking tour and creating my own modern day Mr. Rogers show on YouTube. But most importantly, they will help me continue to be able to be a stay at home parent for Wilder and finally create our own outdoor farm school! More on that coming soon. :) 

Thank you to you everyone who has helped me get here over the last two years. My struggle with mental health will likely never be over, but that's ok, when you're not alone and learn healthy coping skills. Thank you for helping me become the parent who I am today.

Watch out, 2023. Big changes are coming. It's time to stop simply surviving, and time to start thriving. 

If you are a brand interested in collaborating, please contact Hello@TheGoldStudios.com!

These last two years have had some of the hardest moments I've ever experienced, and still, this life with you Wilder Lea is my dream life. 

Here's to being enough as a parent. 

And here's to thriving in 2023.

I'm so deeply grateful for the life that I am living today. These last three years have included some of the hardest moments, but also some of the most profoundly life altering moments that have completely shifted the existence of my life experience. 

Thank you. 

Thank you for still being here and supporting me. 

Thank you for loving me until I could learn to love myself. 

I am worthy. 

I am enough. 

And I will never be the mistakes that I have made.

Some days I'm still in shock that I grew and housed this amazing kid in my very own body. 

Motherhood and women are absolutely sacred. 

But I am not a woman or a mother. 

I am a birthing person. 

Birthing people like me exist and deserve to be included in the language used to describe us and our experiences. 

Trans men and non-binary people birth babies too. 

Including us in that language takes nothing away from your motherhood or your identity as women. We're not asking you to change the way you speak of yourself. But we are asking you to change the way you speak of us, and our families. 

My path to parenthood is just as sacred as yours was to motherhood.
Here's your daily reminder that you too, are enough.

Today is #TransDayOfVisibility! Not only am I a proud trans-masculine person, I'm also a grateful recovering addict. Why do I share that with you on #TransDayOfVisibility though?

Did you know that transgender people are at a significantly greater risk for substance abuse than the general population? In fact up to 30% or trans folks struggle with substance abuse compared to the 9% of the general population who do. 

There are many factors for this including but not limited to: 
 
-increased discrimination and a lack of acceptance 
-family rejection 
-Barriers to health care and treatment 
-minority stress 
-Social and emotional consequences 

As someone who has struggled with substance abuse in the past, it wasn't until I was able to get honest and ask for help.

If you or someone you love may be struggling with addiction, let @americanaddictioncenters hear your story and help you determine a path to treatment. Call their helpline anytime at 866-244-1070. Remember, you are not alone!

If you missed the episode of Dr. Phil that I was on this week, it will be available on his YouTube page 4/18! 

To my trans and non-binary family, please be mindful when watching the ful episode. I haven't watched it yet for self-care reasons.  This was a very hard conversation to have with lots of transphobia rotted within it. Watch with caution and keep your hearts close. You are worthy of carrying a child as a trans/non-binary person and deserve language that represents you. 

To everyone else: please, go watch this. We need your help in creating change and a world that uses inclusive language.

Rowan and Wilder, seahorse babies turned to besties.

This weekend marked one year without my heart dog, Jersey Girl. As it takes time and many tears to create my tribute to her, I want to take a moment to share the gift she's sent since she's been gone.

Miko doesn't fill the hole Jersey left, nor do I ever expect her to. But she's created a new kind of love and relationship in my life that is worthy of its own space in my heart. I wasn't necessarily looking for a Goffin's Cockatoo (I definitely wasn't), but in life I have found that often times our pets choose us before we can choose them. Miko flew right into my life and from the moment she landed on my arm and nudged me to pet her, I knew she'd be a lifelong friend. One that wouldn't replace the pain of grief, but who would instead sit with me while I walk through mine. Miko is teaching me so much about life and patience and myself. She's ignited a new passion in me and highlighting just how much I truly love birds at a time when I need passion the most.

This weekend we went to a new beach, one that would have been an instant favorite of Jersey Girl's. I cried, and smiled while remembering some of the moments we had together and how time after time again, that dog saved my life and kept me in the world. 

The day before camping while I was live on TikTok, someone came into my room with the screen name "Jersey Girl" and a profile picture of a dog. The next day, while pulling up to the state park, I looked through the rear view mirror and gasped, Jersey was there just as she always had been. I blinked and in that moment I saw that it was just the camping chair I had brought with. But it was also so much more. She shows me that she's always with me, especially when I need her the most. 

One day, I'll get another service dog. But until then, I'm going to lean into this new friendship with Miko here, making new memories all along the way.

One of the most common questions I get these days is where is Wilder's other parent? 

But you see, I am Wilder's only parent. And I am enough. Being a parent is a privilege and a title that is earned, not just given. Could that change one day? Absolutely. But we're in today, not tomorrow or the next day. And today, being a sober single parent is the greatest joy of my life. #transdad #singledad #solodad

Guess who's back on regular animals chores and care?! This kid. And me. :) 

Who misses our daily chore adventures and is ready for more farm shenanigans? I sure am and have missed this routine. 

Wilder has grown into such an amazing little farm hand and thrives on being a part of the hard work. 

It's been a week since doing the work regularly again and I can already feel it having a positive impact on my mental and physical health.

I recorded this while Wilder was asleep next to me, can you tell?! 

But also, you don't have to feel like you've been stuck in the wrong body your entire life in order to be trans. In fact, you can even love your body while being trans. Not fitting the common narrative of growing up and feeling stuck in the wrong body kept me from discovering my trans identity for many years. Even when I began my medical transition I felt confused and not quite right until I found the term non-binary. I'm not a man or a woman, I'm Danny. Non-binary people don't have to present as androgynous. And just becuase we may use binary terms sometimes to describe ourselves, like dad or papa, doesn't mean we're not non-binary. 

I discovered language for my identity becuase of other visible trans and non-binary people. My visibility has a purpose and has led me down a path that is worth living. My visibility is a privilege that comes with great responsibility. A responsibility is to use my voice for those who can't and to raise the voices of those who arn't being heard. Just as my elders did for me. 
.
.
.
.
.

Yesterday the universe reminded me why I'm visible as a trans person. 

I had to go to the grocery store in the small town I live in while wearing this sweatshirt. Due to having recieved some hate in the past while wearing certain messages and not having much emotional capacity to recieve possible hate, I contimplated changing before leaving home. It's not something I would typically do, but some days my mental health needs more protecting than others and yesterday was one of those days. 

So I decided to wear my sunglasses (even though it was raining out) and would simply hang them on my sweatshirt to block some of the letters. 

As we're shopping, a store worker approached me, trying to say something while also stumbling on their words. Their energy was big and nervous. And finally they said, "your sweatshirt...." 

"Oh god, here we go" I thought. 

But then, the universe gave me a gift that I wasn't expecting. 

"Your sweatshirt...thank you. Thank you for wearing it, especially here in this town. We need to protect trans kids! I....I know I look like one thing here in front of you, but when I'm at home, I can be my true self, which is a woman. I moved here from Chicago at forty-five years old so I could transition, but it's so scary in this small town and I haven't had the courage to yet. You've helped with that." 

I instantly had tears in my eyes and felt like the air had been knocked out of me. 

I said, "transitioning is scary, really scary. And sometimes living in this town as a trans person can feel scary. In fact, I was scared to come here with this sweatshirt on tonight. But I did it anyway and look what came out of it? I gave birth to my baby (points to Wilder) as a visible trans person.." but before I could finish their energy almost exploded with excitement as they jumped up and down. 

As this person's eyes lit up it hit me, they didn't know I was trans. They assumed I was an ally speaking up for the trans community. They got tears in their eyes, gave me the best feeling fist bump ever, and said "thank you" before quite literally skipping away.

Thank you, @steviebrocksom. I love this sweatshirt and the impact it's had.

Fall on the farm is my absolute favorite. 

Today while we walked, I told Wilder about how leaves change colors and then fall off so new leaves can grow in the spring. We talked about how change is also something that we experience all the time. And how sometimes change is scary, but that the presences of fear doesn't make something bad. It just makes us human. And just like the trees, change creates space for new growth. Growth that has the ability to make our lives feel more vibrant and beautiful, just like the leaves on the trees right before they experience change. 

Just then, Wilder started collecting leaves that had already started falling from the trees and was putting them in their pockets.

"They're so beautiful papa, I want to keep them forever!"

As they did, I told them, "the next time you're feeling scared because something is changing, remember how beautiful these leaves are and how they needed to change in order to be these beautiful colors." 

I thought  that I had been talking to Wilder, but realized tonight that I was talking to myself. Change can feel so scary, but is often necessary to be able to experience growth. It's within the growth, that I find the most beauty. 

Here's to walking through our fears and towards growth.

I don't normally speak politics on my page, but with a platform this size comes a responsibility. A responsibility to speak up and to stand up for those being silenced by genocide. 

The world is watching an ethnic cleansing and genocide of 2 million people (1 million of them being children) happen in real time, right in front of our eyes. 

We must stop sitting in silence while Palestinian children and citizens are being slaughtered. We must speak up for them just as we have for the Israeli's murdered by Hamas. 

Please educate yourself on what's happening in Gaza and Israel and be conscious of your news source. Listen to the stories from those on the ground in Gaza. There are so many lies being spread by major media outlets, celebrities and influencers alike. Even the president of the Unites States was heard lying about seeing photos of the beheading of Israeli children by Hamas, causing outrage. But it wasn't true, there is no picture proof of that happening. Yet at the same time, when it was uncovered that there is, in fact, proof of Palestinian children who have been beheaded by Israeli air strikes on Gaza, those once outraged are suddenly silent. 

With this, I want to make it VERY clear that supporting the end of the occupation in Palestine does not automatically make someone antisemitic. I condemn the actions of the Israeli government, not of the Jewish people. I sympathize with all of the Jewish community this has impacted, while I firmly stand with my Jewish friends and community who are also against the occupation in Palestine. Just as I condem the actions of Hamas, while also acknowledging that they are a product of the occupation. I don't support them or their action. I support the freedom of Palestinian's from Israel and Hamas alike.

We must speak up. This is not a war. This is a genocide. 

I refuse to silently sit on the sidelines of a genocide simply becuase my privilege allows me to, all while our tax dollars are funding war crimes against children and innocent citizens. 

Listen to those being oppressed and to the voices being silenced. Open your eyes and ears to what is really happening. 

Before it's too late.

Mama Dog is settling in so well!

I was nervous about how she would do with the birds, both noise wise and reactivity wise. But I have to say, she has passed with flying colors. She doesn't care one bit about the birds and cares a whole lot about being close to me. I even walk her up to the barn with me twice a day to do farm animals chores and she doesn't bat an eye at the chickens or ducks, even when just feet away from them. 

She does however get overly excited about and chases cats. This is something that we're going to be working a lot on, becuase we have a lot of cats both in the house and outside. I will say, she started chasing one while outside the other day and immediately called off when I recalled her. It was AMAZING and her recall is on point. I wholeheartedly believe her over excitement towards cats can be worked with. 

She is also VERY clingy. Like, crawl inside your skin no matter where you are clingy. Paws your face if you stop petting her clingy. This could very well be becuase of her recent trauma of being dumped combined with her personality. But this is also something that we can and will be working on. I struggle with the constant clingyness as a touched out single parent (and is one of the reasons I had to rehome Wonder during the peak of my Postpsrtum Depression/Pyschosis), but I also deeply appreciate how much she already loves me and wants to be near me. 

If we can work through these two issues, then I don't see mama dog going anywhere unless it's on an adventure with us. 

I know her puppy is the one that caught my eye (and who knows, maybe we'll still end up with a puppy), but I've been looking for an adult dog for almost a year now. I didn't really want a puppy because they are soooo much work (and here I am with six haha). I wanted an adult dog that was good with kids and well, I can't deny that the universe has sent her to me. 

If she doesn't end up staying with us, we will make sure she has the very best home that the best mama dog deserves. 

But for the next month and half, this is right where she'll be.

And then, you were three. 

Wilder is blossoming into the most beautiful version of themselves, filled with such compassion and empathy and curiosity and kindness and shows up in the world in ways that often leave me speechless. 

Three years old. 

Three years of loving you and of growing with you. 

Thank you to everyone who has supported our journey over the last three years. We couldn't have gotten here without our community. 

As Wilder has gotten older, my feelings about showing them on social media have been changing. After educating myself more on safety concerns and the consequences of having your children on social media, especially as a Trans public figure (paired with direct threats to our safety, doxing, and finding my photos on a fetish website), I've moved forward with removing Wilder from social media. I'll no longer be showing their face or making them a main focus in any content. I'll still be sharing my journey and they'll be a part of that, but much more privetly now. 

Many folks have asked if I'd be open to creating a subscription channel or patreon where I share photos with closer followers who have been here since the beginning. I deeply appreciate those of you who have been on this journey with us for so long and I see those of you sad about this change. I personally do not feel comfortable charging people to see photos of my child, nor do I trust the safety of that for my family. I'll talk more about safety in a later post.

The last three years as a parent have taught me that my parenting is about learning right alongside my child, and adapting as we go and grow. 

Thank you for adapting with us and for helping me keep my most precious treasure safe. 

(These balloons were regifted to us and will be used for an art project when we're finished with them vs going into the landfill!)

Life update! 

After two years of living together, our beloved Junebug has moved out and onto their next adventure in life. Junebug very quickly became Wilder's bestie, but also family. 

Immediately after moving in, Junebug drove from Seattle to Portland to help get me during my PPD/PPP crisis and hospitalization. 

When police officers showed up to do a wellness check on my child after being reported to CPS and I refused to let them in, Junebug negotiated showing them a picture and got them to leave. 

When CPS showed up, Junebug reassured them that not only was my child safe, they were also well cared for and loved. 

Whenever I had something that needed assembling, Junebug did it with ease. 

When they could hear struggle in my voice or tone, they would step in and play with Wilder.

When Wilder learned to walk and talk, they were there. 

Junebug was a roommate and not a coparent, but the closest thing to a coparent I've ever known. 

They helped me get closer to being the parent I want to be and start breaking harmful generational cycles. 

They became the family Wilder and I needed these last few years and although in a different way, will continue to be for years to come. 

Here are a few of my favorite Wilder and Junebug moments from the last two years. ❤️
